Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (XAML)

In your `EditProductPage.xaml`, override the back button:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2. ViewModel with Cancel Command

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return; // stay on page
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

## 3. Guard the Hardware/Gesture Back Button

The `CancelCommand` handles the Shell back button, but users can also swipe back or press the Android hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the back arrow with "Cancel" text
- Its `Command` fires instead of default back navigation, so you control the flow
- `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` intercepts swipe-back and hardware back â€” the deferral is **required** for async checks like `DisplayAlert`
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so you only guard backward navigation, not forward
